subject: meta-google: Add support to fetch the USB config from Entity Manager
commitMessage:
meta-google: Add support to fetch the USB config from Entity Manager

The information from Entity Manager is used to override the hardcoded
info which are still required in cases Entity Manager is not supported.

Entity Manager Config Example
```
com.google.gbmc.usb
.Device              property  s         "f0000000.udc"
.ProductId           property  t         123
.ProductName         property  s         "gBMC"
```

```
$ /usr/bin/usb_network.sh --product-id "" --product-name "gBMC" --use-entity-manager gBMC --bind-device ""
Fetching EntityManager USB Info:
PID: 0x7B
Device: "f0000000.udc"
Product Name: "gBMC"
ln: /sys/kernel/config/usb_gadget/g1/configs/c.1/ecm.usb0: File exists
Device "f0000000.udc"
/usr/bin/usb_network.sh: line 148: echo: write error: No such device

$ systemctl status usb_network.service -l
* usb_network.service - USB ECM Gadget
     Loaded: loaded (/lib/systemd/system/usb_network.service; enabled; vendor preset: enabled)
     Active: activating (start) since Thu 1970-01-01 00:00:54 UTC; 29s ago
   Main PID: 769 (usb_network.sh)
     CGroup: /system.slice/usb_network.service
             |- 769 /usr/bin/usb_network.sh --product-id 0x0078 --product-name gBMC --bind-device f0000000.udc --use-entity-manager
(code=exited, status=0/SUCCESS)
   Main PID: 743 (code=exited, status=0/SUCCESS)

Starting USB ECM Gadget...
Failed to create bus message: Invalid argument
Fetching EntityManager USB Info:
PID: 0x0078
Device: f0000000.udc
Product Name: gBMC
Finished USB ECM Gadget.
```

```
$ cat /sys/kernel/config/usb_gadget/g1/idVendor
0x18d1
$ cat /sys/kernel/config/usb_gadget/g1/idProduct
0x0078
$ cat /sys/kernel/config/usb_gadget/g1/UDC
f0000000.udc
```

Change-Id: I7750fbfea7b528dd070c381cc8442635186323fa
Signed-off-by: Willy Tu <wltu@google.com>

Is ping technically enough for this? `busctl call xyz.openbmc_project.EntityManager / org.freedesktop.DBus.Peer Ping`

I don't think so. The entity manager service will be up and pingable before the resources are populataed properly.

```
$ systemctl restart xyz.openbmc_project.EntityManager
$ busctl tree xyz.openbmc_project.EntityManager
`-/xyz
  `-/xyz/openbmc_project
    `-/xyz/openbmc_project/EntityManager
$ busctl call xyz.openbmc_project.EntityManager / org.freedesktop.DBus.Peer Ping
$ busctl tree xyz.openbmc_project.EntityManager
`-/xyz
  `-/xyz/openbmc_project
    `-/xyz/openbmc_project/EntityManager
```

If we try to check the entity manager at this point, it will miss the resources.

As written this doesn't seem like enough.  Configurations can be populated or depopulated at any time, which this seems to make the assumption can only be created.  This script is rapidly (pretty sure we're already there) getting to the level of complixity where it shouldn't be a bash script anymore, and ideally needs some unit tests.  I don't know of any race-free, functionally correct EM reactors that have been written in bash (this is not to say people haven't tried).

Take with the above advice what you wish.

there is also plan that we want to support multiple USB interfaces. So maybe it is good time to move away from bash before more complexity gets added.

We can add it to https://github.com/openbmc/google-misc and I can convert the existing feature for now to verify that it works.

William, any thoughts?
supported in https://gbmc-review.googlesource.com/c/meta-gbmc-staging/+/1580 for now, Will need to migrate it upstream if possible.
Prefer using `SECONDS` over an arbitrary value as it reflects the monotonic time since the script started. This accounts for any time spent in the busctl call too.
oh nice. I have updated to use SECONDS.
Are we sure the subtree paths always exist immediately when the top-level object is ready? I suspect this isn't how EM is designed.

yeah, I don't think so. But since we don't know the exact path, this is the best that we can wait for. Or we have to get closer to the motherboard path like

```
/xyz/openbmc_project/inventory/system/board
```

to be more sure.

yeah, I think
```
/xyz/openbmc_project/inventory/system/board
```

will be better assuming that only the mothereboard will have this.
Yeah, you should just hardcode that as the wait for now so we can get a stable change in.
Done

I cherry-picked this CL for VL. Looks like it created an race between phosphor-ipmi-net@usb0.service and usb_network.service. phosphor-ipmi-net@usb0.service will try to start before usb_network.service and it will fail because the network is not up. As a result, none of the host tool can talk with IPMI. As a workaround, I have to add Before=phosphor-ipmi-net@usb0.service to usb_network.service.
